'''Jacques Bernard Modeste d'Anselme''' (22 July 1740, [[Apt, Vaucluse|Apt]] - 17 September 1814, [[Paris]]) was a French general of the [[French Revolutionary Army]], notable as the first commander of the ''[[Army of the Var]]'' which soon became the ''[[Army of Italy (France)|Army of Italy]]''. He fell under suspicion, was removed from command and placed under arrest, but he survived the [[Reign of Terror]]. '''ANSELME''' is one of the [[names inscribed under the Arc de Triomphe]], on Column 23.

==Biography==
He became a [[knight of Saint Louis]] on 18 April 1770. During the [[American Revolutionary War|American Revolution]], he was a lieutenant colonel of the [[Regiment of Soissons]]. As lieutenant general, he took [[County of Nice|Nice]] and the fortresses of Mont Alban ({{lang-fr|[[:fr:Fort du mont Alban|Fort du mont Alban]]}}) and [[Villefranche-sur-Mer]] in 1792, but was defeated at [[Sospel]]lo and imprisoned until the [[Thermidorian Reaction|revolution of Thermidor]].{{sfn|Wilson & Fiske|1900}} His name is inscribed on the [[Arc de Triomphe]].

